\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 11. H. coris} L., {\i Sp. Pl.} 787 (1753). Low shrub, or perennial herb with woody base. Stems 10-45 cm, erect or ascending from creeping and rooting base. Leaves 4-18 mm, in whorls of 4 (rarely 3), glabrous. Flowers in elongated or pyramidal panicles, rarely solitary. Sepals glandular-denticulate, or with sessile, marginal black glands. Petals and stamens persistent. Capsule with longitudinal and oblique, swollen vittae.{\i  Sunny, calcareous rocks. • N. & C. Italy, Switzerland, S.E. France.} Ga He It.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 12. H. ericoides} L., {\i Sp. Pl. }785 (1753). Dwarf shrub. Stems 2-12(-25) cm, erect, with strict branching and short internodes. Leaves 1·5-3·5 mm, in whorls of 4, densely papillose. Flowers in corymbs or panicles. Sepals shortly glandular-ciliate or entire. Petals and stamens persistent. Capsule with narrow, longitudinal vittae.{\i  Sunny, calcareous rocks. E. & S.E. Spain.} Hs.
\par

